<div id="overview" style="display:none;">
    <div class="content">
        <p>
        <h1>Game Specification</h1>
        <br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Title</h2>
        The title for this web based game is "Web Siege", we feel this title is justified from the goal of the game. 
		Users will be able to siege there opponents in any way they see fit using multiple tactics in an environment that allows them to plan attacks from both below and high advantages with different weapons catering to different situations.
        <br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Genre</h2>
        The genre of this game is classed as " Indie Shooter". Two dudes, are an Independant studio that is building a web based game that relies on shooting the opponent.
        <br/>
		<br/>
		<h2>Concept</h2>
		The object of the game is to kill as many players without being killed. The more you kill your tally will rise towards the kill limit. Players are free to use tactical approaches using the levels environment and switching between guns to cater to their positional advantages.
        <br/>
		<br/>
		<h2>Core Objective</h2>
		The goal is to kill as many players as possible, tallying up points towards the kill limit by using unique characters and loadouts. 
		Players are encouraged to use each characters main ability to win to their advantage. However, not all abilities will be beneficial in certain situations and will require a cooldown after used. 
		<br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Expected Experience</h2>
        Players are expected to have fun and feel a sense of laughter from the game. This game is not to resemble reality. Players are also to feel a little adrenaline rush from the speed at which the game can be played at. 
        <br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Purpose</h2>
		The purpose of the game is to have a flowing fun multiplayer shooter where users can create and track their stats as they fill some free time playing out free game. We want to have also created a platform for some competitiveness between users and friends.
        <br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Game Structure</h2>
		In web-siege we have a number of states implemented into the structure of the game.
		<br/>
		<br/>
		<ul>
		<li><h3>Boot  </h3> We have a boot state that initialises a phaser game and frameworks.<li/>
		<li><h3>Load  </h3> A load state that preloads all assets of the game including gun and level sprites.<li/>
		<li><h3>Pre-menu  </h3> A premenu that will require the players to log in to the games server to retrieve their match stats.<li/>
		<li><h3>Menu  </h3> A menu state to browse their stats or play the game.<li/>
		<li><h3>Play  </h3> A play state which will preload level data from the server and initalise the current level.<li/>
		<li><h3>Game  </h3> A game state which will create the current level and draw the map along this state is also responsible for creating a player sprite.<li/>
		<ul/>
		<br/>
		We have a server running that controls all passing data sent to active players through client code and an entity code to update the players status ie health.
		<br/>
		At the end of the game another state will be called into play called the endgame state, this state will show performance ingame and send data to a external database which the pre-menu state will have access to. To retrieve stats and display them.
        <br/>
		<br/>
        <h2>Features Implemented</h2>
		<h3>SQL</h3>
		Database using SQL. We have implemented a database to hold player stats, weapons stats, weapon ammo, match stats. Matches, users and maps
		<br/>
		<h3>Node</h3>
		We are running a server using NODE, currently this is only reachable via localhost. There is talk of going to an external hosted ip.
		<br/>
		<h3>Socket.IO</h3>
		We used Socket.IO as our multiplayer plugin.
		<br/>
		<h3>Player Mechanics</h3>
		<ul>
		<li>W = Jump<li/>
		<li>A = Moves Left<li/>
		<li>D = Moves Right<li/>
		<li>Mouse look handles the crosshair.<li/>
		<li>LMB = Fire<li/>
